{
  "title":"ORDINARY LEVEL NATIONAL EXAMINATIONS ACADEMIC YEAR 2023 – 2024 PHYSICS I",
   "description":"NATIONAL EXAMINATION AND SCHOOL INSPECTION AUTHORITY",
   "timeLimit":180,
   "passingScore":70,
   "sections":[
      {
         "name":"A",
         "title":"SECTION A – COMPULSORY (55 MARKS)",
         "description":"Attempt ALL questions in this section.",
         "questions":[
            {
               "questionNumber":1,
               "text":"Complete each sentence below using the most appropriate term from the box. Each term may be used once or not at all.",
               "type":"fill-in-blank",
               "points":3,
               "wordBank":[
                  "Magnetized",
                  "Magnetic field",
                  "Demagnetized",
                  "Magnetic pole"
               ],
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"A ................................ is a region at each end of a magnet where the magnetic field is strongest.",
                     "type":"fill-in-blank",
                     "points":1,
                     "correctAnswer":"Magnetic pole"
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"b)",
                     "text":"The area around a magnet in which it can exert a magnetic force is called ................................",
                     "type":"fill-in-blank",
                     "points":1,
                     "correctAnswer":"Magnetic field"
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"c)",
                     "text":"At around 80°C, a magnet will become ................................ permanently if exposed to this temperature for a prolonged period.",
                     "type":"fill-in-blank",
                     "points":1,
                     "correctAnswer":"Demagnetized"
                  }
               ],
               "correctAnswer":"a) Magnetic pole, b) Magnetic field, c) Demagnetized"
            },
            {
               "questionNumber":2,
               "text":"Identify the answer choice that best completes each statement or answers each question.",
               "type":"multiple-choice",
               "points":4,
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"The communication channel refers to:",
                     "type":"multiple-choice",
                     "points":1,
                     "options":[
                        {
                           "text":"the message being transmitted",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"the physical location where communication takes place",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"the medium through which the message is transmitted",
                           "isCorrect":true
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"the person initiating the communication",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"iii) the medium through which the message is transmitted"
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"b)",
                     "text":"Which of the following cables transmits signals in the form of light?",
                     "type":"multiple-choice",
                     "points":1,
                     "options":[
                        {
                           "text":"Co-axial cable",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"Fiber optic cable",
                           "isCorrect":true
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"Wire pair cable",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"Twisted pair cable",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"ii) Fiber optic cable"
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"c)",
                     "text":"The circuit shown in Figure 1 represents an amplifier circuit. The electronic components shown are:",
                     "type":"multiple-choice",
                     "points":1,
                     "options":[
                        {
                           "text":"resistor, inductor, transistor",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"resistor, capacitor, transistor",
                           "isCorrect":true
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"resistor, capacitor, ordinary diode",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"resistor, transistor, zener diode",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"ii) resistor, capacitor, transistor"
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"d)",
                     "text":"Which of the following electronic components is a semiconductor device?",
                     "type":"multiple-choice",
                     "points":1,
                     "options":[
                        {
                           "text":"Connecting wire",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"Inductor",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"Capacitor",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"Ordinary diode",
                           "isCorrect":true
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"iv) Ordinary diode"
                  }
               ],
               "correctAnswer":"a) iii) the medium through which the message is transmitted, b) ii) Fiber optic cable, c) ii) resistor, capacitor, transistor, d) iv) Ordinary diode"
            },
            {
               "questionNumber":3,
               "text":"Complete the following statements by selecting the correct term from the given alternatives.",
               "type":"multiple-choice",
               "points":4,
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"Which of the following is a fixed point about which a lever rotates or pivots?",
                     "type":"multiple-choice",
                     "points":1,
                     "options":[
                        {
                           "text":"Effort",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"Load",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"Fulcrum",
                           "isCorrect":true
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"Pulley",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"iii) Fulcrum"
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"b)",
                     "text":"The Mechanical Advantage of a simple machine is:",
                     "type":"multiple-choice",
                     "points":1,
                     "options":[
                        {
                           "text":"effort / load",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"load / effort",
                           "isCorrect":true
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"load + effort",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"load - effort",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"ii) load / effort"
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"c)",
                     "text":"The Velocity Ratio of a simple machine is the ratio of the distance travelled by the ......... to the distance travelled by the ......... in the same machine.",
                     "type":"multiple-choice",
                     "points":1,
                     "options":[
                        {
                           "text":"load; load",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"effort; load",
                           "isCorrect":true
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"load; effort",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"effort; effort",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"ii) effort; load"
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"d)",
                     "text":"All vehicles move with the help of the simple machine called:",
                     "type":"multiple-choice",
                     "points":1,
                     "options":[
                        {
                           "text":"wheel and axle",
                           "isCorrect":true
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"inclined plane",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"wedge",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"screw",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"i) wheel and axle"
                  }
               ],
               "correctAnswer":"a) iii) Fulcrum, b) ii) load / effort, c) ii) effort; load, d) i) wheel and axle"
            },
            {
               "questionNumber":4,
               "text":"State whether each of the following statements is TRUE or FALSE.",
               "type":"true-false",
               "points":4,
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"The pressure exerted by a static liquid increases linearly with increasing depth.",
                     "type":"true-false",
                     "points":1,
                     "correctAnswer":true
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"b)",
                     "text":"Ice floats on water because ice has a lower density than water.",
                     "type":"true-false",
                     "points":1,
                     "correctAnswer":true
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"c)",
                     "text":"A force acting on a larger surface area of an object exerts a larger pressure.",
                     "type":"true-false",
                     "points":1,
                     "correctAnswer":false
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"d)",
                     "text":"Relative density of a substance is the ratio of the density of water to the density of the substance.",
                     "type":"true-false",
                     "points":1,
                     "correctAnswer":false
                  }
               ],
               "correctAnswer":"a) TRUE, b) TRUE, c) FALSE, d) FALSE"
            },
            {
               "questionNumber":5,
               "text":"State whether each of the following statements is TRUE or FALSE.",
               "type":"true-false",
               "points":3,
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"A car parked at the top of a hill possesses potential energy.",
                     "type":"true-false",
                     "points":1,
                     "correctAnswer":true
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"b)",
                     "text":"A ball dropped from a height h towards the earth surface is an example of kinetic energy being converted into potential energy.",
                     "type":"true-false",
                     "points":1,
                     "correctAnswer":false
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"c)",
                     "text":"Geothermal energy is heat produced by burning natural gas.",
                     "type":"true-false",
                     "points":1,
                     "correctAnswer":false
                  }
               ],
               "correctAnswer":"a) TRUE, b) FALSE, c) FALSE"
            },
            {
               "questionNumber":6,
               "text":"Select the correct answer among the given alternatives.",
               "type":"multiple-choice",
               "points":4,
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"The diagram (Figure 2) shows the electric field pattern produced by two point electric charges A and B. Which row correctly indicates the nature of the charges A and B?",
                     "type":"multiple-choice",
                     "points":1,
                     "options":[
                        {
                           "text":"A = Positive, B = Positive",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"A = Positive, B = Negative",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"A = Negative, B = Negative",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"A = Negative, B = Positive",
                           "isCorrect":true
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"iv) A = Negative, B = Positive"
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"b)",
                     "text":"The amount of force exerted on a unit positive charge placed in an electric field is known as:",
                     "type":"multiple-choice",
                     "points":1,
                     "options":[
                        {
                           "text":"electric potential",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"electric flux",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"electric field intensity",
                           "isCorrect":true
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"electric current",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"iii) electric field intensity"
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"c)",
                     "text":"What is the magnitude of the electric potential V at a distance d from an electric charge Q?",
                     "type":"multiple-choice",
                     "points":1,
                     "options":[
                        {
                           "text":"Q / (4πε₀d)",
                           "isCorrect":true
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"9 × 10⁶ × Q/d",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"9 × 10⁹ × Q/d²",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"6.67 × 10⁻¹¹ × Q/d",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"i) Q / (4πε₀d)"
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"d)",
                     "text":"Which one of the following is an application of Electrostatics?",
                     "type":"multiple-choice",
                     "points":1,
                     "options":[
                        {
                           "text":"Electric motor",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"Electric generator",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"Paint spraying",
                           "isCorrect":true
                        },
                        {
                           "text":"Electromagnet",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"iii) Paint spraying"
                  }
               ],
               "correctAnswer":"a) iv) A = Negative, B = Positive, b) iii) electric field intensity, c) i) Q / (4πε₀d), d) iii) Paint spraying"
            },
            {
               "questionNumber":7,
               "text":"Match the physical quantities in Column A with their correct dimensional formulae in Column B.",
               "type":"matching",
               "points":4,
               "leftItems":[
                  "Speed",
                  "Density",
                  "Acceleration",
                  "Energy"
               ],
               "rightItems":[
                  "[ML²T⁻²]",
                  "[LT⁻¹]",
                  "[ML⁻³]",
                  "[LT⁻²]"
               ],
               "correctMatches":{
                  "Speed":"[LT⁻¹]",
                  "Density":"[ML⁻³]",
                  "Acceleration":"[LT⁻²]",
                  "Energy":"[ML²T⁻²]"
               },
               "correctAnswer":"Speed → [LT⁻¹], Density → [ML⁻³], Acceleration → [LT⁻²], Energy → [ML²T⁻²]"
            },
            {
               "questionNumber":8,
               "text":"Differentiate between a renewable and a non-renewable energy source.",
               "type":"open-ended",
               "points":4,
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"Differentiate between a renewable and a non-renewable energy source.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":2,
                     "correctAnswer":"Renewable energy sources can be naturally replenished in a short time and are available indefinitely (e.g., solar, wind). Non-renewable energy sources took millions of years to form and cannot be replaced once used (e.g., fossil fuels)."
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"b)",
                     "text":"Give ONE example of each of the following:",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":2,
                     "subQuestions":[
                        {
                           "label":"i)",
                           "text":"A renewable energy source:",
                           "type":"open-ended",
                           "points":1,
                           "correctAnswer":"Any one of: solar energy, wind power, hydroelectric power, geothermal energy, biomass"
                        },
                        {
                           "label":"ii)",
                           "text":"A non-renewable energy source:",
                           "type":"open-ended",
                           "points":1,
                           "correctAnswer":"Any one of: coal, petroleum/oil, natural gas, uranium/nuclear fuel, minerals"
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"i) Any one of: solar energy, wind power, hydroelectric power, geothermal energy, biomass; ii) Any one of: coal, petroleum/oil, natural gas, uranium/nuclear fuel, minerals"
                  }
               ],
               "correctAnswer":"a) Renewable energy sources can be naturally replenished in a short time and are available indefinitely (e.g., solar, wind). Non-renewable energy sources took millions of years to form and cannot be replaced once used (e.g., fossil fuels). b) i) Any one of: solar energy, wind power, hydroelectric power, geothermal energy, biomass; ii) Any one of: coal, petroleum/oil, natural gas, uranium/nuclear fuel, minerals"
            },
            {
               "questionNumber":9,
               "text":"You are given four statements:",
               "type":"open-ended",
               "points":3,
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"Which of the above statements is an example of instantaneous velocity?",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":1,
                     "correctAnswer":"Statement C: At t=1s, a runner is moving at 4 m/s west"
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"b)",
                     "text":"Justify your answer.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":2,
                     "correctAnswer":"It specifies both the speed (4 m/s), the direction (west), and the exact instant in time (t = 1 s). Instantaneous velocity requires speed, direction, and a specific point in time."
                  }
               ],
               "correctAnswer":"a) Statement C: At t=1s, a runner is moving at 4 m/s west; b) It specifies both the speed (4 m/s), the direction (west), and the exact instant in time (t = 1 s). Instantaneous velocity requires speed, direction, and a specific point in time."
            },
            {
               "questionNumber":10,
               "text":"The following diagram (Figure 3) represents electricity generation, transmission, and distribution.",
               "type":"open-ended",
               "points":4,
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"Why is the efficiency of a real transformer less than 100%?",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":1,
                     "correctAnswer":"Real transformers have losses due to: (i) resistance (copper) losses in the coil windings, and (ii) eddy current and hysteresis losses in the iron core / magnetic flux leakage."
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"b)",
                     "text":"Explain why thicker electric wires are preferable for long-distance electricity transmission.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":1,
                     "correctAnswer":"Thicker wires have lower electrical resistance (R = ρL/A; larger A = lower R). Lower resistance means less power lost as heat (P = I²R), making transmission more efficient."
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"c)",
                     "text":"Identify the type of transformers on the poles shown in Figure 3.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":1,
                     "correctAnswer":"Step-down transformer (the distribution transformer reduces high transmission voltage to household level)."
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"d)",
                     "text":"State ONE reason why electricity is very important at home.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":1,
                     "correctAnswer":"Electricity at home is used for lighting, heating/cooling, powering appliances (TV, radio, computer, refrigerator, etc.)."
                  }
               ],
               "correctAnswer":"a) Real transformers have losses due to: (i) resistance (copper) losses in the coil windings, and (ii) eddy current and hysteresis losses in the iron core / magnetic flux leakage. b) Thicker wires reduce resistance. c) Step-down transformer. d) For lighting, heating, powering appliances, etc."
            },
            {
               "questionNumber":11,
               "text":"The diagram (Figure 4) shows a brick being pushed by a force F on an unsmooth horizontal table.",
               "type":"open-ended",
               "points":4,
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"The pushing force does not make the brick move. Explain why:",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":2,
                     "subQuestions":[
                        {
                           "label":"i)",
                           "text":"The brick does not move sideways:",
                           "type":"open-ended",
                           "points":1,
                           "correctAnswer":"The pushing force is equal to or less than the friction force, so the net horizontal force is zero – the brick remains stationary."
                        },
                        {
                           "label":"ii)",
                           "text":"The weight of the brick does not make it move downwards:",
                           "type":"open-ended",
                           "points":1,
                           "correctAnswer":"The weight (downward force) is exactly balanced by the normal reaction force from the table surface (Newton's 3rd Law)."
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"i) The pushing force is equal to or less than the friction force. ii) The weight is balanced by the normal reaction force."
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"b)",
                     "text":"A different pushing force makes the brick slide across the table from rest.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":2,
                     "subQuestions":[
                        {
                           "label":"i)",
                           "text":"Does the linear momentum P of the brick increase, decrease, or remain constant? Explain.",
                           "type":"open-ended",
                           "points":1,
                           "correctAnswer":"Linear momentum P = mv increases, because the constant resultant force causes constant acceleration (Newton's 2nd Law: F=ma), increasing velocity over time."
                        },
                        {
                           "label":"ii)",
                           "text":"State ONE thing that the sliding brick does to the unsmooth table surface.",
                           "type":"open-ended",
                           "points":1,
                           "correctAnswer":"The sliding brick generates heat (friction converts kinetic energy to thermal energy) and/or produces sound."
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"i) Linear momentum increases. ii) The brick generates heat and/or produces sound."
                  }
               ],
               "correctAnswer":"a) i) The pushing force is equal to or less than the friction force. ii) The weight is balanced by the normal reaction force. b) i) Linear momentum increases. ii) The brick generates heat and/or produces sound."
            },
            {
               "questionNumber":12,
               "text":"A vehicle having rectilinear motion is moving with an initial velocity of 10 m/s and accelerates uniformly to 15 m/s over a distance of 125 m.",
               "type":"open-ended",
               "points":4,
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"What is the acceleration of the vehicle?",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":2,
                     "correctAnswer":"0.5 m/s²"
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"b)",
                     "text":"What is the time taken to cover this distance?",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":2,
                     "correctAnswer":"10 s"
                  }
               ],
               "correctAnswer":"a) 0.5 m/s², b) 10 s"
            },
            {
               "questionNumber":13,
               "text":"When an electric current of 4 A passes through a resistor for 10 minutes, 2.88 × 10⁴ J of heat are produced.",
               "type":"open-ended",
               "points":3,
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"Convert the electric energy E = 2.88 × 10⁴ J into kilowatt-hours (kWh).",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":1,
                     "correctAnswer":"0.008 kWh"
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"b)",
                     "text":"Calculate the voltage across the resistor.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":2,
                     "correctAnswer":"12 V"
                  }
               ],
               "correctAnswer":"a) 0.008 kWh, b) 12 V"
            },
            {
               "questionNumber":14,
               "text":"Figure 6 shows an alternating current (AC) circuit comprising a pure capacitor and AC generator connected in series.",
               "type":"open-ended",
               "points":4,
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"If the frequency f of the electromotive force of the AC generator is increased, what will be the effect on:",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":2,
                     "subQuestions":[
                        {
                           "label":"i)",
                           "text":"The impedance of the electric circuit? Justify your answer.",
                           "type":"open-ended",
                           "points":1,
                           "correctAnswer":"Impedance decreases. For a capacitor, Z = Xₙ = 1/(2πfC). As f increases, Z decreases (inversely proportional)."
                        },
                        {
                           "label":"ii)",
                           "text":"The rms electric current flowing through this electric circuit? Justify your answer.",
                           "type":"open-ended",
                           "points":1,
                           "correctAnswer":"rms current increases. Iᵣₘₛ = Vᵣₘₛ / Z = Vᵣₘₛ × 2πfC. As f increases, Iᵣₘₛ increases (directly proportional)."
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"i) Impedance decreases. ii) rms current increases."
                  }
               ],
               "correctAnswer":"a) i) Impedance decreases. ii) rms current increases."
            },
            {
               "questionNumber":15,
               "text":"What would happen to the Earth without the hydrosphere?",
               "type":"open-ended",
               "points":3,
               "correctAnswer":"Without the hydrosphere: There would be no liquid water on Earth's surface. Living cells could not carry out normal functions – all life would cease to exist. There would be no habitat for aquatic organisms (fish, crocodiles, etc.). No evaporation, so no clouds could form, meaning no rainfall and no precipitation. Desertification would cover the entire planet. The climate regulation provided by oceans would be lost, leading to extreme temperature variations."
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "name":"B",
         "title":"SECTION B – ATTEMPT ANY THREE QUESTIONS (30 MARKS)",
         "description":"Attempt any THREE (3) questions from this section.",
         "questions":[
            {
               "questionNumber":16,
               "text":"When light passes through a lens, it is refracted at both faces of the lens.",
               "type":"open-ended",
               "points":10,
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"Copy the diagram (Figure 7) into your answer booklet and complete the path of the light ray through the section of the lens.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":2,
                     "correctAnswer":"Draw the diagram with the light ray passing through the lens."
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"b)",
                     "text":"Draw a ray diagram to show the formation of a virtual image in a converging lens.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":2,
                     "correctAnswer":"Draw the ray diagram for a converging lens."
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"c)",
                     "text":"A converging lens of focal length 25 cm and a diverging lens of focal length -10 cm are placed in contact.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":4,
                     "subQuestions":[
                        {
                           "label":"i)",
                           "text":"Calculate the power of the converging lens.",
                           "type":"open-ended",
                           "points":2,
                           "correctAnswer":"Power of converging lens: P₁ = 1/f = 1/0.25 m = +4 D"
                        },
                        {
                           "label":"ii)",
                           "text":"Calculate the power of the diverging lens.",
                           "type":"open-ended",
                           "points":1,
                           "correctAnswer":"Power of diverging lens: P₂ = 1/f = 1/(-0.10 m) = -10 D"
                        },
                        {
                           "label":"iii)",
                           "text":"Calculate the power of the combination of these lenses.",
                           "type":"open-ended",
                           "points":1,
                           "correctAnswer":"Total power: P = P₁ + P₂ = 4 + (-10) = -6 D"
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"i) +4 D, ii) -10 D, iii) -6 D"
                  }
               ],
               "correctAnswer":"a) Draw the diagram. b) Draw the ray diagram. c) i) +4 D, ii) -10 D, iii) -6 D"
            },
            {
               "questionNumber":17,
               "text":"You are provided with the following electrical circuit components:",
               "type":"open-ended",
               "points":10,
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"Draw an electric circuit diagram showing the arrangement of the given laboratory materials.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":3,
                     "correctAnswer":"Draw the circuit diagram with the given components."
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"b)",
                     "text":"State the procedures to be followed and the measurements to be taken.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "points":3,
                     "correctAnswer":"Procedure: Connect the circuit as drawn. Close the switch. Set the rheostat to different positions to vary the current. For each setting, record the ammeter reading (I) and the voltmeter reading (V). Repeat for at least 5 different current values."
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"c)",
                     "text":"Analyse the data collected during measurements.",
